\layout Section

Subdivision schemes
\layout Standard

Interpolatory subdivision schemes where first introduced by Deslauriers
 and Dubuc (quote).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula \( b>1 \)
\end_inset 

 be an integer, given two integers 
\begin_inset Formula \( k,j \)
\end_inset 

, the number 
\begin_inset Formula \( x_{j,k}=k/b^{j} \)
\end_inset 

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula \( b- \)
\end_inset 

adic (of depth 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \)
\end_inset 

).
 For a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \)
\end_inset 

, the 
\begin_inset Formula \( b- \)
\end_inset 

adic numbers form a regularly-spaced set of nodes.
 Given some corresponding data 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\{ y_{J,k}\right\} _{k\in \N } \)
\end_inset 

 on the dyadic numbers of depth 
\begin_inset Formula \( J \)
\end_inset 

, we want to build a smooth fonction 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \( f\left( x_{J,k}\right) =y_{J,k}\, \forall k\in \N  \)
\end_inset 

.
 Starting with this initial data (
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{J,k} \)
\end_inset 

) and using the linear formula 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{basicsubdivision}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma _{bk-l}y_{j,k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for some constant array 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma  \)
\end_inset 

, we get values 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{J,k} \)
\end_inset 

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula \( j>J \)
\end_inset 

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula \( b- \)
\end_inset 

adic numbers form a dense set of the real numbers, there is at most one
 continuous function such that 
\begin_inset Formula \( f\left( x_{j,k}\right) =y_{j,k} \)
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula \( k,j>J \)
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

A subdivision scheme is interpolatory and will satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula \( f\left( x_{J,k}\right) =y_{J,k} \)
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{bk}=0 \)
\end_inset 

 except when 
\begin_inset Formula \( k=0 \)
\end_inset 

.
 We say that a subdivision scheme is stationary if the array 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma  \)
\end_inset 

 is constant (doesn't depend on 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \)
\end_inset 

).
 An interpolatory subdivision scheme is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2N- \)
\end_inset 

points if 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{l}=0 \)
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula \( |l|>Nb \)
\end_inset 

.
 The interpolation function 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 computed from a 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2N- \)
\end_inset 

points 
\begin_inset Formula \( b- \)
\end_inset 

adic scheme with initial data 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{0,0}=1 \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{0,k}=0 \)
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula \( k\neq 0 \)
\end_inset 

 is said to be the fundamental function and has a compact support of 
\begin_inset Formula \( [-(Nb-1)/(b-1),(Nb-1)/(b-1)] \)
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula \( [1-2N,2N-1] \)
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula \( b=2 \)
\end_inset 

.
 Hence as 
\begin_inset Formula \( N \)
\end_inset 

 increases the support of the fundamental function increases.
\layout Standard

For each 
\begin_inset Formula \( N=1,2,3,... \)
\end_inset 

 there exists a corresponding an interpolatory Deslauriers-Dubuc subdivision
 scheme and they are built from the midpoint evaluation of Lagrange polynomial
 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2N-1 \)
\end_inset 

 on 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2N \)
\end_inset 

 points.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula \( b=2 \)
\end_inset 

 (dyadic case), the 
\begin_inset Formula \( 4- \)
\end_inset 

points Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme can be defined by the array 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma ^{DD2} \)
\end_inset 

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{0}^{DD2}=1,\,  \)
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{1}^{DD2}=\gamma ^{DD2}_{-1}=-9/16,\,  \)
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{3}^{DD2}=\gamma _{-3}^{DD2}=-1/16 \)
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{k}^{DD2}=0 \)
\end_inset 

 otherwise; for 
\begin_inset Formula \( b=4 \)
\end_inset 

 (tetradic case), the scheme is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma ^{DD4} \)
\end_inset 

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma ^{DD2}_{k}\, \forall k\in \N ,\,  \)
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{-1}^{DD4}=\gamma _{1}^{DD4}=105/128,\,  \)
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{-3}^{DD4}=\gamma _{-3}^{DD4}=35/128,\,  \)
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{-5}^{DD4}=\gamma _{5}^{DD4}=-7/128,\,  \)
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{-7}^{DD4}=\gamma _{7}^{DD4}=-5/128,\,  \)
\end_inset 

with 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{k}^{DD2}=0 \)
\end_inset 

 otherwise.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula \( 4- \)
\end_inset 

points Deslauriers-Dubuc schemes are derived from cubic Lagrange polynomials,
 they reproduces cubic polynomials, that is, if the initial data 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,k} \)
\end_inset 

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,k}=p\left( x_{j,k}\right) \, \forall k\in \N  \)
\end_inset 

 for some cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula \( p \)
\end_inset 

 then the interpolation function 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 is this same cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula \( f=p \)
\end_inset 

.
 Hence the two cases presented above (
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma ^{DD2} \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma ^{DD4} \)
\end_inset 

) reproduce cubic polynomials.
 It can also be shown also that they both give differentiable (
\begin_inset Formula \( C^{1} \)
\end_inset 

) interpolation functions.
\layout Standard

We are interested in measuring how well a given subdivsion scheme can approximat
ion functions.
 One such measure is given by the approximation order of the scheme
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite[definition 2]{KuVD98}

\end_inset 

.
 We say that a subdivision scheme has approximation order 
\begin_inset Formula \( p \)
\end_inset 

 if given given any smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula \( g\in C^{p}\left( \left[ 0,1\right] \right)  \)
\end_inset 

, the interpolation function 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \( f\left( x_{j,k}\right) =g\left( x_{j,k}\right) \, \forall k\in \N  \)
\end_inset 

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\Vert f-g\right\Vert _{L^{\infty }\left( \left[ 0,1\right] \right) }\leq C/2^{jp} \)
\end_inset 

 for a constant 
\begin_inset Formula \( C \)
\end_inset 

 independent of 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

For a continuous subdivision scheme reproducing polynomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula \( p \)
\end_inset 

, it is sufficient for the scheme to converge to a continous function to
 have approximation order 
\begin_inset Formula \( p+1 \)
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{KuVD98}

\end_inset 

.
 Specifically, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula \( 4- \)
\end_inset 

points Deslauriers-Dubuc schemes have approximation order 
\begin_inset Formula \( 4 \)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Section

High resolution subdivsion schemes
\layout Subsection

Definitions
\layout Standard

An more general alternative to equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{basicsubdivision}

\end_inset 

 is given by the linear equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{m=1}^{N}\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma _{Nbk+m-1-l}^{(m)}y_{j,Nk+m-1}\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma ^{(1)},...,\gamma ^{(N)} \)
\end_inset 

 are constant arrays (independent from 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \)
\end_inset 

).
 Because this new formula uses 
\begin_inset Formula \( N \)
\end_inset 

 times the usual number of nodes (see equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{basicsubdivision}

\end_inset 

), we say that it is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

high resolution subdivision scheme
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 however it can still be said to be 
\begin_inset Formula \( b- \)
\end_inset 

adic because the number of nodes is increasing by 
\begin_inset Formula \( b \)
\end_inset 

.
 As a special case, when 
\begin_inset Formula \( N=1 \)
\end_inset 

, we have a usual subdivision scheme.
 
\layout Standard

In what follows, we set 
\begin_inset Formula \( b=N=2 \)
\end_inset 

 and consider the equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{N2highres}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma _{4k-l}^{(1)}y_{j,2k}+\gamma _{4k+1-l}^{(2)}y_{j,2k+1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\gamma ^{(1)}_{k} & = & \gamma ^{DD4}_{k}-\alpha \frac{\left( (-1)^{k}+1\right) }{2}\gamma ^{DD2}_{k/2}+\alpha \delta _{k,0}\, \forall k\in \N \label{N2highres_1} \\
\gamma ^{(2)}_{0} & = & \alpha ,\, \gamma ^{(2)}_{k}=0\, otherwise\label{N2highres_2} 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 for some parameter 
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha \in \R  \)
\end_inset 

.
 As we will see, this choice is made so that the scheme can reproduce cubic
 polynomials for all 
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha  \)
\end_inset 

.
 The odd terms 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\{ y_{j,2k+1}\right\} _{k\in \N } \)
\end_inset 

will be referred as placeholders because their assigned value will change
 in general.
 In the simplest case, 
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha =0 \)
\end_inset 

, equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{N2highresalpha0}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma ^{DD4}_{4k-l}y_{j,2k}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Because 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma ^{(2)}=0 \)
\end_inset 

 in this case, we can see that the placeholders are effectively ignored.
 Indeed, we observe that this last equation discards odd terms at each step:
 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j+1,l} \)
\end_inset 

 depends only on terms of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,2k} \)
\end_inset 

 (even terms) and not at all on the odd terms 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,2k+1} \)
\end_inset 

.
 Hence, we can replace equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highresalpha0}

\end_inset 

 by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{j+1,2l}=\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma ^{DD4}_{4k-2l}y_{j,2k}\]

\end_inset 

but because 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma ^{DD2}_{k} \)
\end_inset 

 , this last equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j+1,2l}=\gamma ^{DD2}_{2k-l}y_{j,2k} \)
\end_inset 

 and if we define 
\begin_inset Formula \( \widetilde{y}_{j,k}=y_{j,2k} \)
\end_inset 

 then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{DD2}
\widetilde{y}_{j+1,2l}=\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma ^{DD2}_{2k-l}\widetilde{y}_{j,2k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

which we recognize as the cubic Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme.
 
\layout Proposition


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{propDesDuequiv}

\end_inset 

For 
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha =0 \)
\end_inset 

, the high resolution scheme given by equations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_1}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_2}

\end_inset 

 is equivalent to the 
\begin_inset Formula \( 4- \)
\end_inset 

points dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc subdivision scheme (discarding the odd nodes
 or placeholders in the first iteration).
\layout Standard

In general, since 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma ^{DD2}_{k} \)
\end_inset 

, we can rewrite equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 for even and odd terms.
 Firstly, setting 
\begin_inset Formula \( l=2s \)
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset Formula \( l \)
\end_inset 

 even), we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
y_{j+1,2s} & =\sum _{k\in \N } & \gamma _{4k-2s}^{(1)}y_{j,2k}+\gamma _{4k+1-2s}^{(2)}y_{j,2k+1}\\
 & =\sum _{k\in \N } & \left( \gamma ^{DD4}_{4k-2s}-\alpha \gamma ^{DD2}_{2k-s}+\alpha \delta _{4k,2s}\right) y_{j,2k}+\alpha \delta _{4k+1,s}y_{j,2k+1}\\
 & =\sum _{k\in \N } & \left( (1-\alpha )\gamma ^{DD2}_{2k-s}+\alpha \delta _{2k,s}\right) y_{j,2k}+\delta _{2k+1,s+1}\alpha y_{j,2k+1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

so that when 
\begin_inset Formula \( s \)
\end_inset 

 is even (
\begin_inset Formula \( l=2s=4r \)
\end_inset 

), we have the interpolatory condition 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{hrsinterpole}
y_{j+1,4r}=y_{j,2r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

otherwise, when 
\begin_inset Formula \( s \)
\end_inset 

 is odd 
\begin_inset Formula \( (l=2s=4r+2) \)
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{hrsricharson}
y_{j+1,4r+2}=\alpha y_{j,2r+1}+(1-\alpha )\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma ^{DD2}_{2k-2r-1}y_{j,2k}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Secondly, if 
\begin_inset Formula \( l \)
\end_inset 

 is odd (
\begin_inset Formula \( l=2s+1 \)
\end_inset 

), we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
y_{j+1,2s+1} & = & \sum _{k\in \N }\gamma _{4k-2s-1}^{(1)}y_{j,2k}+\gamma _{4k-2s-1}^{(2)}y_{j,2k+1}\\
 & = & \sum _{k\in \N }\gamma ^{DD4}_{4k-2s-1}y_{j,2k}.\label{hrswidguess} 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

Equations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsinterpole}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsricharson}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrswidguess}

\end_inset 

 can be used to describe the chosen high resolution schemes: while qquation
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsinterpole}

\end_inset 

 is the interpolatory condition, equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrswidguess}

\end_inset 

 fills the placeholders with tetradic (coarse scale) interpolated values
 whereas equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsricharson}

\end_inset 

 combines the value stored in the placeholder with the newly available interpola
ted value (fine scale) given by the summation term which we recognize from
 the dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc interpolation.
 
\layout Subsection

Reproduced polynomials
\layout Standard

Assume that for some 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \)
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,k}=p_{3}\left( x_{j,k}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

 for some cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula \( p_{3} \)
\end_inset 

.
 We then have that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma ^{DD2}_{2k-2r-1}y_{j,2k}=y_{j,2r+1}=p_{3}\left( x_{j,2r+1}\right) \]

\end_inset 

and thus equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsricharson}

\end_inset 

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j+1,4r+2}=p_{3}\left( x_{j,2r+1}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

 .
 Moreover, equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrswidguess}

\end_inset 

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j+1,2s+1}=p_{3}\left( x_{j+1,2s+1}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

.
 We can conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j+1,k}=p_{3}\left( x_{j+1,k}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,k}=p_{3}\left( x_{j,k}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

.
 For practical implementations of a high subdivision scheme, it is necessary
 to first apply a one-step subdivision scheme since in general, we don't
 have placeholder values precomputed.
 This can be achieved with a dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc filter.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\{ y_{j,k}\right\} _{k} \)
\end_inset 

 be some initial data.
 As a first step, we apply equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{DD2_2}
y_{j+1,2l}=\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma ^{DD2}_{2k-l}y_{j,2k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 followed by equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula \( j=j+1 \)
\end_inset 

, and so on.
 By induction, we get the following lemma.
\layout Lemma

The high resolution scheme given by equations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_1}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_2}

\end_inset 

 (using 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{DD2_2}

\end_inset 

 as an initialization step) reproduces cubic polynomials.
\layout Standard

We can also get a stronger result by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha  \)
\end_inset 

.
 Let 
