\layout Subsection

Sufficient conditions for regularity
\layout Standard

To study the regularity of high resolution schemes, it is convenient rewrite
 formula 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 in terms of (trigonometric) polynomials.
 Given some data 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,k} \)
\end_inset 

, define 
\begin_inset Formula \( P^{j}(z)=\sum _{k\in \N }y_{j,k}z^{k} \)
\end_inset 

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula \( P_{2}(z)=\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma _{k}^{DD2}z^{k} \)
\end_inset 

, then equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{DD2_2}

\end_inset 

, can be rewritten 
\begin_inset Formula \( P^{j+1}(z)=P_{2}(z)P^{j}(z^{2}) \)
\end_inset 

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula \( P_{4}(z)=\sum _{k\in \N }\gamma _{k}^{DD4}z^{k} \)
\end_inset 

, then the tetradic subdivision scheme is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \( P^{j+1}(z)=P_{4}(z)P^{j}(z^{2}) \)
\end_inset 

.
 
\begin_inset Formula \( \mathrm{I} \)
\end_inset 

t can be shown that we can rewrite the general equation for high resolution
 subdivision schemes as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P^{j+1}(z)=\sum _{i=1}^{M}\Gamma _{i}(z)P^{j}\left( e^{2\pi i/b}z^{b}\right) .\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma _{i} \)
\end_inset 

 must be Laurent polynomials.
 Using symbols, equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
P^{j+1}(z) & = & \left\{ P_{4}\left( z\right) -\alpha P_{2}\left( z^{2}\right) +\alpha \right\} \left( \frac{P^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) +P^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) }{2}\right) +\alpha \left( \frac{P^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) -P^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) }{2}\right) \\
 & = & \left\{ \frac{P_{4}\left( z\right) -\alpha P_{2}\left( z^{2}\right) }{2}+\alpha \right\} P^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) +\frac{P_{4}\left( z\right) -\alpha P_{2}\left( z^{2}\right) }{2}P^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) \\
 & = & \Gamma _{1}(z)P^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) +\Gamma _{2}(z)P^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) \label{gammas} 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

Because 
\begin_inset Formula \( \gamma _{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma ^{DD2}_{k}\, \forall k\in \N  \)
\end_inset 

, we observe that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P_{4}\left( z\right) -\alpha P_{2}\left( z^{2}\right) =\frac{P_{4}\left( z\right) -P_{4}\left( -z\right) }{2}+(1-\alpha )\frac{P_{4}\left( z\right) +P_{4}\left( -z\right) }{2}\]

\end_inset 

and thus
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\Gamma _{1}(z) & = & \Gamma _{2}(z)+\alpha \\
\Gamma _{2}(z) & = & \frac{P_{4}\left( z\right) -P_{4}\left( -z\right) }{4}+(1-\alpha )\frac{P_{4}\left( z\right) +P_{4}\left( -z\right) }{4}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

When 
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha =0 \)
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma _{1}(z)=\Gamma _{2}(z)=\frac{P_{4}\left( z\right) }{2} \)
\end_inset 

 and equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
P^{j+1}(z)=P_{4}\left( z\right) \left( \frac{P^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) +P^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) }{2}\right) \]

\end_inset 

and it can be shown to be equivalent to the Deslauriers-Dubuc dyadic scheme
 by writing
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{P^{j+1}(z)+P^{j+1}(-z)}{2} & = & \left( \frac{P_{4}\left( z\right) -P_{4}\left( -z\right) }{2}\right) \left( \frac{P^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) +P^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) }{2}\right) \\
 & = & P_{2}\left( z^{2}\right) \left( \frac{P^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) +P^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) }{2}\right) .
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

which gives an alternate proof for proposition 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{propDesDuequiv}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

In order to study the regularity and stability of the chosen high resolution
 schemes, we need to find corresponding schemes for the (forward) finite
 differences 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{dy_{j,k}}{dx_{j,k}}=\frac{y_{j,k+1}-y_{j,k}}{1/2^{j}}\]

\end_inset 

and of the correspondin higher order finite differences which can be defined
 recursively 
\begin_inset Formula \( d^{(n)}y_{j,k}=d\left( d^{(n-1)}y_{j,k}\right) /(dx_{j,k})^{n} \)
\end_inset 

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
H_{1}^{j}(z) & = & \sum _{k\in \N }2^{j}\left( y_{j,k+1}-y_{j,k}\right) z^{k}\\
 & = & \sum _{k\in \N }2^{j}y_{j,k}z^{k-1}-\sum _{k\in \N }2^{j}y_{j,k}z^{k}\\
 & = & 2(1/z-1)P^{j}(z)=2(1-z)P^{j}(z)/z,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 then 
\begin_inset Formula \( P^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) =z^{2}2^{j}H_{1}^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) /(1-z^{2}) \)
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \( P^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) =-z^{2}2^{j}H_{1}^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) /(1+z^{2}) \)
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula \( P^{j+1}(z)=z2^{j+1}H_{1}^{j+1}(z)/(1-z) \)
\end_inset 

.
 Substituting these equations into 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{gammas}

\end_inset 

 gives
\begin_inset Formula \[
H_{1}^{j+1}(z)=\frac{2z(1-z)}{(1-z^{2})}\Gamma _{1}(z)H_{1}^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) -\frac{2z(1-z)}{(1+z^{2})}\Gamma _{2}(z)H_{1}^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) .\]

\end_inset 

 The higher order finite differences are given by
\begin_inset Formula \[
H_{n}^{j}(z)=\frac{2(1-z)}{z}H_{n-1}^{j}(z)=\left( \frac{2(1-z)}{z}\right) ^{n}P^{j}(z)\]

\end_inset 

where we let 
\begin_inset Formula \( H_{0}(z)=P(z) \)
\end_inset 

 and it can be seen that higher order finite differences are related through
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{genh}
H_{n}^{j+1}(z)=\left( \frac{2z}{1+z}\right) ^{n}\Gamma _{1}(z)H_{n}^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) +\left( \frac{-2z(1-z)}{1+z^{2}}\right) ^{n}\Gamma _{2}(z)H_{n}^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) .
\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \( H_{n} \)
\end_inset 

 is said to be equivalent to a high resolution subdivision scheme if 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma _{1}(z)/(1+z) \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma _{2}(z)/(1+z^{2}) \)
\end_inset 

 are Laurent polynomials.
 However, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
P_{4}(z)=\frac{-\left( 1+z\right) ^{4}\left( 1+z^{2}\right) ^{4}\left( 5z^{2}-12z+5\right) }{128z^{7}}\]

\end_inset 

and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma _{2}(z)/(1+z^{2})^{n} \)
\end_inset 

 is a Laurent polynomial for 
\begin_inset Formula \( \textrm{n}=1,2,3,4 \)
\end_inset 

.
 On the other hand, we can also show that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma _{1}(z)/(1+z)^{n} \)
\end_inset 

 is a Laurent polynomial for 
\begin_inset Formula \( n=1,2,3,4 \)
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula \( H_{n} \)
\end_inset 

 is the symbol of a high resolution subdivision scheme if 
\begin_inset Formula \( n=1,2,3,4 \)
\end_inset 

.
 While 
\begin_inset Formula \( H_{n} \)
\end_inset 

 is equivalent to the subdivision scheme of 
\begin_inset Formula \( d^{(n)}y_{j,k}/(dx_{j,k})^{n}=2^{jn}d^{(n)}y_{j,k} \)
\end_inset 

, we can define 
\begin_inset Formula \( dH_{n}^{j} \)
\end_inset 

 based on 
\begin_inset Formula \( d\left( 2^{j(n-1)}d^{(n-1)}y_{j,k}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

 with, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula \( dH_{1}^{j}(z)=(1-z)P^{j}(z)/z \)
\end_inset 

 and more generally 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{dHdef}
dH_{n-1}^{j}(z)=\frac{(1-z)}{z}H_{n-1}^{j}(z)=\frac{2^{j(n-1)}(1-z)^{n}}{z^{n}}P^{j}(z).
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula \( H_{n-1} \)
\end_inset 

 by 
\begin_inset Formula \( dH_{n-1} \)
\end_inset 

 in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{genh}

\end_inset 

, we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{dH}
2dH_{n-1}^{j+1}(z)=\left( \frac{2z}{1+z}\right) ^{n}\Gamma _{1}(z)dH_{n-1}^{j}\left( z^{2}\right) +\left( \frac{-2z(1-z)}{1+z^{2}}\right) ^{n}\Gamma _{2}(z)dH_{n-1}^{j}\left( -z^{2}\right) .
\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \( dH_{n-1} \)
\end_inset 

 is said to be equivalent to a high resolution subdivision scheme if 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma _{1}(z)/(1+z)^{n} \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Gamma _{2}(z)/\left( 1+z^{2}\right) ^{n} \)
\end_inset 

 are Laurent polynomials or if 
\begin_inset Formula \( H_{n} \)
\end_inset 

 is equivalent to a high resolution subdivision scheme which is true for
 
\begin_inset Formula \( n=1,2,3,4 \)
\end_inset 

.
